rnational collection of cognitive and functional linguists, offers an outline of original empirical work carried out in grounding theory. Grounding is a central notion in cognitive grammar that addresses the linking of semantic content to contextual factors that constitute the subjective ground (or situation of speech). The volume illustrates a growing concern with the application of cognitive grammar to constructions establishing deixis and reference. It proposes a double focus on nominal and clausal grounding, as well as on ways of integrating analyses across these domains.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCognitive grammar. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxDeixis. 0aReference (Linguistics). 4aDeixis. 4aKognitive Grammatik. 4aKongress. 4aReferenz ‹Linguistik›. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aAchard, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrisard, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrisard, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoiz-Bienzobas, Aintzane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpstein, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanssen, Theo A. J. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKochańska, Agata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangacker, Ronald W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaury, Ritva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMortelmans, Tanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulder, Walter De, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNuyts, Jan, econt